void set_heartbeat_function(string sEffectID, int iTicks,
 status tReverse, mixed xTickMessage, mixed xEndMessage,
 string sFunction, mixed *axVariables, int iNoTick)

sEffectID - this should be a unique ID. it does a check
-- on that ID, and fails if it's already in use.

iTicks - how many heartbeat ticks will it go for.

tReverse - reverse whatever arg you called onto the player.
-- this means the value is only set at the start, and removed
-- at the end, and not every tick.

xTickMessage - will give a room_message(({TO}),ENV(TO),
-- sTickMessage) each tick. if you don't wish to have a message,
-- you need to put in a 0.

xEndMessage - will give a room_message(({TO}),ENV(TO),
-- xEndMessage) at the last tick. if you don't wish to have
-- a message, you need to put in a 0.

sFunction - the function that will be called on TO.
-- Examples: "add_con", "receive_damage"
-- To dispatch to an object carried by TO, use "call_inventory_lfun" and
-- pass ({ object ID, function name, ({ persistent arguments }) }). The
-- carried object's function receives TO as its first argument. This avoids
-- saving an object reference in the heartbeat effect.

axVariables - the args that will get passed to the sFunction.
-- Examples: ({ -10 }),({10,WEAPON_PIERCE,0,TP})

iNoTick - if set to 1, the function will only be called at the
-- the start, and not every tick and end. if set to 0, the function
-- will be called every tick, unless tReverse is also set. if set
-- to -1, the function will only be called on the last tick, and
-- not at the start or every tick. if set to 1 or -1, tReverse
-- should never be set, as they are contradictory.

The room_message for the messages will only use the target object
for the messages, and not the object instigating the action. That
is why it doesn't have a start message, that would still be done
in a guild command, room, object, etc.

The functions that can make use of tReverse are the simple functions
where you only set and remove single args. For functions that require
more args, you would make use of iNoTick, and make 2 unique calls
with opposite values.

Example calls:
oTarget->set_heartbeat_function("thomas_test",15,1,"$N $vfeel\
 weaker.","$N $vfeel better.","add_con",({-10}),0);
oTarget->set_heartbeat_function("thomas_test_dot",15,0,"$N $vare\
 wracked by pain!","$N $vare no longer wracked by pain.",
"receive_damage",({100,DAM_MAGIC,0,TP}),0);

Example calls using iNoTick:
oTarget->set_heartbeat_function("thomas_MR_start",30,0,0,0,
 "add_natural_resistance",({ DAM_MAGIC, 10 }),1);
oTarget->set_heartbeat_function("thomas_MR_end",30,0,0,
 "$N $vare no longer protected against magic!",
"add_natural_resistance",({ DAM_MAGIC, -10 }),-1);

Example calling a carried object without persisting that object:
oTarget->set_heartbeat_function("example_inventory_tick",15,0,0,0,
 "call_inventory_lfun",
 ({ "example_soul", "effect_tick", ({ 10, "source" }) }),0);
// Calls example_soul->effect_tick(oTarget, 10, "source").

mapping query_heartbeat_functions() will return the mapping
so you can check for unique IDs.

int check_heartbeat_function(string sEffectID) will check if
the "sEffectID" is an active heartbeat function on the living
object. Returns 0 if it is not present, 1 if it is.

void clear_heartbeat_function(string sEffectID)
  This function will try and clear the heartbeat function.
  It will change the ticks to 0, and end the function,
  doing whatever the function would have done.
  If you have multiple functions like a _start and _end,
  you should clear them all at the same time.

If a player logs off while the function is running, it will
pick up the ticks from where it left off, while applying the args
again as if it had just started. Therefor, make sure that any
args you set on a player are ones that clear when a player
logs off, like add_<stat>, add_natural_resistance, etc.
If you are not sure, test it :)

To register an effect as a *debuff* (visible in the player's `buffs`
list but not removable via `clearbuff`), add an entry to
GLOBAL_DEBUFF_MAPPING in secure/include/buffs.h. Effects not in either
mapping remain invisible to the `buffs` UI but still tick down normally.

Do not use heartbeat callbacks to implement Burning, Bleeding, Chilled,
Freezing, or Exposed. Those are living-owned status effects; use the
apply_status_effect() API documented by `funhelp apply_status_effect` and
`wizhelp 9.16`.
